In this nomenclature the modular group $\Gamma$ is called the modular group of level 1 and denoted 
as $\Gamma(1)$ \cite{McKean,Diamond}. A relevant mathematical structure is the coset of the modular group with 
the congruence subgroups which are isomorphic to $PSL(2, \mathbb{Z}/N \mathbb{Z})$ \cite{Diamond}

text:
\begin{equation}
\Gamma(N)=\left \{ 
\left( \begin{matrix}
a & b \\
c & d 
\end{matrix} \right) \subset SL(2, \mathbb{Z}):
\left( \begin{matrix}
a & b \\
c & d 
\end{matrix} \right) = 
\left( \begin{matrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 1 
\end{matrix} \right) \, (\mbox{mod} \, N) \right \}.
\end{equation}

